"""
mkt-context: Zechariah ch8-13 — comprehensive historical/ANE background commentary (92 verses).
Chs 8 = ten restoration oracles; chs 9-11 = First Burden (nations + rejected shepherd);
chs 12-13 = Second Burden begins (Jerusalem's deliverance, the pierced one, the smitten shepherd).
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-zechariah-8-13.py
"""
import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent


def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    return json.loads(p.read_text()) if p.exists() else {}


def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=2))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')


def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, text in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = text


DATA = {
    "8": {
        "1": "<p>Chapter 8 contains ten oracles of restoration (vv2, 3, 4, 6, 7, 9, 14, 19, 20, 23), each introduced by 'Thus says the LORD of hosts.' This structural pattern — the repeated messenger formula — emphasizes the divine authority behind each promise. The chapter directly reverses the six curses of 7:10-14: judgment and desolation (ch7) become restoration and joy (ch8). The ten-oracle pattern may reflect the ten plagues (reversing judgment into blessing) or simply the common use of ten as a number of completeness.</p>",
        "2": "<p>'I am zealous for Zion with great zeal, and I am zealous for her with great wrath.' The intensity of YHWH's zeal for Jerusalem is double: zeal for Zion and anger against her enemies — both expressed with the same root <em>qana</em> (to be zealous, H7065). This verse echoes 1:14-15: the same divine passion that was the ground of the night visions' promises is restated as the ground of the restoration oracles. YHWH's zeal for his city is not diminished by the exile; it is intensified by the nations' complacency (1:15).</p>",
        "3": "<p>'I have returned to Zion and will dwell in the midst of Jerusalem, and Jerusalem shall be called the faithful city, and the mountain of the LORD of hosts, the holy mountain.' Three titles for restored Jerusalem: (1) <em>ir ha'emet</em> (the faithful/truthful city) — the city that was once characterized by lying officials (7:10) becomes characterized by faithfulness; (2) <em>har YHWH tzvaot</em> (the mountain of the LORD of hosts) — the universal Zion theology of Isa 2:2-4, Mic 4:1-3; (3) <em>har haqodesh</em> (the holy mountain) — the dwelling of YHWH's holiness in the midst of the city. The transformation of Jerusalem from corrupt capital to holy city is the eschatological promise that the NT applies to the new Jerusalem (Rev 21:2).</p>",
        "4": "<p>'Old men and old women shall again sit in the streets of Jerusalem, each with staff in hand because of great age.' The demographic portrait of restored Jerusalem: the very old (staff-using elderly) and the very young (boys and girls playing in the streets) coexist in safety. This is the inverse of the siege and exile: in the Babylonian destruction, the elderly and children were the most vulnerable and most likely to die or be taken (Lam 2:20-21; 5:11-14). Their return to public space is the sign of shalom — when the vulnerable are safe in public, the society is at peace.</p>",
        "5": "<p>'And the streets of the city shall be full of boys and girls playing in its streets.' The children playing (<em>mesahaqim</em>, from <em>sachaq</em> = to laugh, play, H7832) are the sign of normalcy restored. In ancient cities under threat, children did not play in public — they were kept inside for safety. Playing children in the streets is the biblical image of total peace: Isa 11:8 (the nursing child shall play over the hole of the cobra); Jer 30:19 (from them shall come songs of thanksgiving and voices of those who celebrate). The eschatological city is characterized by the safety of the most vulnerable.</p>",
        "6": "<p>'Thus says the LORD of hosts: If it is marvelous in the eyes of the remnant of this people in those days, should it also be marvelous in my eyes, declares the LORD of hosts?' The challenge to human incredulity: what seems impossible (<em>yippaleh</em>, H6381 — too wonderful/marvelous, beyond ordinary capacity) to the remnant is not impossible to YHWH. The word <em>pele</em> (wonder, miracle) is used for YHWH's Exodus acts (Exod 15:11; Ps 78:12) — the impossible has happened before in Israel's history. The remnant's disbelief in restoration is understandable; YHWH's ability is not limited by their experience.</p>",
        "7": "<p>'Thus says the LORD of hosts: Behold, I will save my people from the east country and from the west country.' The ingathering from both east (<em>eretz mizrach hashamesh</em> = land of the rising sun) and west (<em>eretz mevo hashamesh</em> = land of the setting sun) is the universal compass of the return from exile. Not just from Babylon in the east but from every direction — the prophetic vision of ingathering expands beyond the historical return from Persia to a universal eschatological gathering of the scattered people. The NT fulfillment: Matt 8:11 (many will come from east and west and recline at table with Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob in the kingdom of heaven).</p>",
        "8": "<p>'And I will bring them to dwell in the midst of Jerusalem. And they shall be my people, and I will be their God, in faithfulness and in righteousness.' The covenant-restoration formula: <em>vehayu li le'am va'ani ehyeh lahem lElohim</em> (they shall be my people and I will be their God). This is the fundamental covenant formula of Sinai (Exod 6:7; Lev 26:12; Jer 7:23; 11:4; 30:22; 31:33; 32:38; Ezek 36:28; 37:27) — the broken covenant restored. The qualifiers <em>be'emet uvitzedaqah</em> (in faithfulness and in righteousness) describe both YHWH's character in restoration and the quality of the restored relationship.</p>",
        "9": "<p>'Thus says the LORD of hosts: Let your hands be strong, you who in these days have been hearing these words from the mouths of the prophets who were present on the day that the foundation of the house of the LORD of hosts was laid, that the temple might be built.' The encouragement to strengthen hands (<em>techezaqna yedeikhem</em>, the same command as Hag 2:4) is addressed to the temple-building generation. The contrast with the pre-building period (vv10-11: wages were few, enemies many) and the promise of the new period (v12: the vine shall give its fruit) grounds the exhortation: YHWH's past abandonment of the people and his present blessing of their work.</p>",
        "10": "<p>'For before those days there was no wage for man or any wage for beast, neither was there any safety from the foe for him who went out or came in, for I set every man against his neighbor.' The pre-building desolation (520-516 BCE era of Haggai's early oracles, Hag 1:6-11; 2:15-17) was divine discipline: economic futility and social conflict. The word <em>shalach</em> (I set every man against his neighbor) implies divine orchestration of the social conflict — covenant curse producing covenant breakdown. The reversal in v12 is correspondingly comprehensive.</p>",
        "11": "<p>'But now I will not deal with the remnant of this people as in the former days, declares the LORD of hosts.' The pivotal 'but now' (<em>ve'atah lo ... kiyamim harishonim</em>) — the turning point between the old dispensation of judgment and the new dispensation of blessing. The 'former days' are the period of covenantal discipline that produced the exile and the post-exilic economic hardship. The new period is characterized by YHWH's positive relationship with the remnant.</p>",
        "12": "<p>'For there shall be a sowing of peace. The vine shall give its fruit, and the ground shall give its produce, and the heavens shall give their dew. And I will cause the remnant of this people to possess all these things.' The 'sowing of peace' (<em>zera hashalom</em>) — either a seed of peace planted, or a peaceful/fruitful sowing season. The list of natural blessings (vine, ground, heavens, dew) reverses Hag 1:10-11 (I called for a drought on the land... it withheld its produce). The covenant blessing cycle of Deut 28:3-5 (blessed in field, vine, sky, land) is restored. The remnant will inherit all these blessings.</p>",
        "13": "<p>'And as you have been a byword of cursing among the nations, O house of Judah and house of Israel, so will I save you, and you shall be a blessing. Fear not, but let your hands be strong.' The reversal of covenant curse to covenant blessing: Israel was used as a curse-formula among the nations ('may you become like Israel!') — now it will become a blessing-formula (cf. Isa 65:16). The pairing of Judah and Israel — both houses of the divided kingdom — is the eschatological reunification that Ezekiel 37:15-23 promises: the two sticks become one in YHWH's hand.</p>",
        "14": "<p>'For thus says the LORD of hosts: As I purposed to bring disaster to you when your fathers provoked me to anger, and I did not relent, says the LORD of hosts.' The divine constancy that executed judgment is the same divine constancy that will now execute blessing. The un-relenting consistency of YHWH (he did not relent from judgment, Lam 2:17) becomes the guarantee of blessing: the same determination that brought disaster will bring restoration. YHWH's purposes stand — both for judgment and for blessing.</p>",
        "15": "<p>'So again have I purposed in these days to bring good to Jerusalem and to the house of Judah; fear not.' The parallel structure: as YHWH purposed disaster in response to covenant violation, he now purposes good (<em>hetavoti</em>) in response to the covenant's restoration promise. The theological point: YHWH's blessing is not a reversal of his character (as if he changed his mind) but the fulfillment of his covenant commitment, which always included both curse and blessing. The two-sided character of YHWH's covenantal commitment means both the judgment and the restoration were always his purpose.</p>",
        "16": "<p>'These are the things that you shall do: Speak the truth to one another; render in your gates judgments that are true and make for peace.' The ethical imperatives for the restored community: (1) <em>emet dabru</em> (speak truth) — the opposite of the lying leaders of 7:10; (2) <em>mishpat emet veshalom shafetu</em> (render judgments of truth and peace in your gates) — the gate was the site of legal proceedings in ancient Israel (Ruth 4:1-11; Amos 5:10-15). The legal system restored to truthful adjudication is the social foundation of the restored city.</p>",
        "17": "<p>'Do not devise evil in your hearts against one another, and love no false oath, for all these things I hate, declares the LORD.' The two prohibitions correspond to the covenant command of 7:10 (let none devise evil in his heart against another): internal malice and external perjury. <em>Hate</em> is strong covenant language (cf. Prov 6:16-19: seven things YHWH hates; Amos 5:21: I hate, I despise your feasts) — YHWH's moral opposition is absolute. The restoration community's ethical character must reflect the city's new name: <em>ir ha'emet</em> (the faithful city, v3).</p>",
        "18": "<p>'And the word of the LORD of hosts came to me, saying.' The introduction to the oracle about the fasts (vv19-23) completes the response to the Bethel delegation's question of 7:3 about the fifth-month fast. YHWH's answer has taken chs 7-8 to develop: the negative (fasting done for self, not YHWH, is worthless) leads to the positive (the fasts will become feasts of joy when YHWH restores).</p>",
        "19": "<p>'Thus says the LORD of hosts: The fast of the fourth month and the fast of the fifth and the fast of the seventh and the fast of the tenth shall be to the house of Judah seasons of joy and gladness and cheerful feasts. Therefore love truth and peace.' The four fasts that commemorated the stages of Jerusalem's fall are transformed into feasts: (1) the fourth-month fast (17 Tammuz = day the city wall was breached, 2 Kgs 25:3-4; Jer 39:2); (2) the fifth-month fast (9 Ab = day the temple was burned, 2 Kgs 25:8-9); (3) the seventh-month fast (Gedaliah's assassination, 2 Kgs 25:25); (4) the tenth-month fast (10 Tevet = when the siege of Jerusalem began, 2 Kgs 25:1). The four memorial fasts of national disaster become four festivals of national joy — the grief of destruction transformed into celebration of restoration.</p>",
        "20": "<p>'Thus says the LORD of hosts: Peoples shall yet come, even the inhabitants of many cities.' The eschatological vision of vv20-23: the nations streaming to Jerusalem is the Zion eschatology of Isa 2:2-4; Mic 4:1-3. Unlike those passages, which describe nations going up to the mountain, Zechariah's vision shows the nations approaching Jews in the streets and asking to accompany them: 'Let us go with you, for we have heard that God is with you' (v23). The universal recognition of YHWH through his people.</p>",
        "21": "<p>'The inhabitants of one city shall go to another, saying, Let us go at once to entreat the favor of the LORD and to seek the LORD of hosts; I myself am going.' The urgency of the seeking nations: <em>holekh gam ani</em> (I myself am going/already going) — the individual declaration that joins the corporate movement. The seeking of YHWH's favor (<em>lechalot et penei YHWH</em>, to entreat the face of YHWH) is the same vocabulary as the Bethel delegation's question (7:2). The nations do spontaneously what the Bethel delegation did deliberately — seek YHWH.</p>",
        "22": "<p>'Many peoples and strong nations shall come to seek the LORD of hosts in Jerusalem and to entreat the favor of the LORD.' The expansion from one city (v20-21) to <em>amim rabbim vegoyim atzumim</em> (many peoples and strong nations) — including powerful nations, not just weak ones seeking protection. The nations' seeking of YHWH in Jerusalem is the fulfillment of Solomon's prayer at the temple dedication (1 Kgs 8:41-43: when the foreigner comes and prays toward this house, hear from heaven).</p>",
        "23": "<p>'Thus says the LORD of hosts: In those days ten men from the nations of every tongue shall take hold of the robe of a Jew, saying, Let us go with you, for we have heard that God is with you.' The famous 'ten men per Jew' verse: ten (<em>asarah anashim</em> = ten men — perhaps representing a minyan, the quorum for Jewish prayer) from every tongue/language clinging to the robe of a Jew, following him to Jerusalem. The nations' perception that God is with Israel ('we have heard that God is with you', <em>shama'nu ki Elohim imakhem</em>) is the reversal of the exile's scandal: the exile made it appear that YHWH had abandoned Israel; the restoration makes it clear that YHWH is with them. The NT fulfillment: Gentiles joining themselves to the Jewish Messiah and his Jewish apostles (Acts 2:41, 47; 11:21; 14:27).</p>"
    },
    "9": {
        "1": "<p>Chapter 9 begins the 'First Burden' (<em>massa</em>, H4853 = oracle, burden) of Zechariah — the first of two oracles (chs 9-11 and 12-14) that are structurally distinct from the dated night-vision section (chs 1-8). The undated character and the different style of chs 9-14 ('Deutero-Zechariah') have led many scholars to posit different authorship, though the unity of the book remains defensible. The First Burden opens with a geo-political sweep from north (Hadrach, Damascus) to south (Philistia), pronouncing judgment on the nations surrounding Israel — similar to the oracles-against-the-nations in Amos 1-2 and Jeremiah 46-51.</p>",
        "2": "<p>'And Hamath also, which borders on it, Tyre and Sidon, though they are very wise.' The northern nations (Hamath on the Orontes, the commercial metropolises of Tyre and Sidon) are addressed. Tyre and Sidon were renowned for their wisdom in ancient tradition (Ezek 28:3-5: your wisdom and your understanding) — their commercial acumen made them wealthy and proud. Their wisdom (<em>chakkam meod</em>) could not protect them from the divine judgment that the oracle pronounces.</p>",
        "3": "<p>'Tyre has built herself a rampart and heaped up silver like dust, and fine gold like the mud of the streets.' Tyre's legendary impregnable island fortress (an engineering marvel of the ancient world) and her accumulated wealth are described. The comparison 'silver like dust' (<em>keturar kesef</em>) and 'gold like mud of the streets' echoes Job 27:16 (if he heaps up silver like dust) — the accumulation that will be swept away. Alexander the Great fulfilled this oracle in 332 BCE, destroying Tyre by building a causeway to the island fortress (the debris of the mainland city was cast into the sea — fulfilling Ezek 26:12).</p>",
        "4": "<p>'But behold, the Lord will strip her of her possessions and strike down her power on the sea, and she will be devoured by fire.' The divine judgment on Tyre's wealth and naval power: <em>vehorisha</em> (will dispossess her), <em>vahikka bayam cheilah</em> (will strike her power/wealth in the sea), <em>vahi be'esh teikhal</em> (she will be devoured by fire). Alexander's siege and destruction of Tyre (332 BCE) fulfilled this precisely: the city was besieged, its wealth was captured, and much of it was burned. The prophetic word authenticated by specific historical fulfillment was a pillar of OT apologetics (Deut 18:22).</p>",
        "5": "<p>'Ashkelon shall see it and be afraid; Gaza too, and shall writhe in anguish; Ekron also, because its hopes are confounded. The king shall perish from Gaza; Ashkelon shall be uninhabited.' The Philistine cities witnessing Tyre's destruction will be paralyzed with fear — and then face their own judgment. The four Philistine cities (Ashkelon, Gaza, Ekron, Ashdod in v6) were the same targets as Zeph 2:4-7. Gaza (<em>Azzah</em>) losing her king echoes the wordplay of Zeph 2:4 (<em>Azzah azuva</em> = Gaza forsaken).</p>",
        "6": "<p>'A mixed people shall dwell in Ashdod, and I will cut off the pride of Philistia.' <em>Mamzer</em> (H4464 — a person of mixed/uncertain ancestry, translated 'mixed people' or 'bastard') settling in Ashdod signals the dissolution of Philistine ethnic identity. The 'pride of Philistia' (<em>ga'on plishtim</em>) — the cultural, military, and political achievements that made the Philistines proud — will be cut off. The Philistine pentapolis as a coherent political entity effectively disappeared after the Hellenistic period.</p>",
        "7": "<p>'I will take away its blood from its mouth, and its abominations from between its teeth; it too shall be a remnant for our God; it shall be like a clan in Judah, and Ekron shall be like the Jebusites.' The astonishing promise: after judgment, a Philistine remnant will join the people of God. 'Taking blood from its mouth' (removing the abomination of blood-eating, forbidden in the Mosaic law, Lev 17:14) represents purification. The Jebusite comparison is the most powerful: the Jebusites, inhabitants of Jerusalem before David (2 Sam 5:6-8), were absorbed into Israel after conquest. Similarly, the purified Philistine remnant will be incorporated into God's people — an early anticipation of Gentile inclusion.</p>",
        "8": "<p>'Then I will encamp at my house as a guard, so that none shall march to and fro; no oppressor shall again march over them, for now I see with my own eyes.' YHWH promises to guard his house (the temple/land) personally — he himself as the sentry. 'No oppressor shall again march over them' — after the sequence of Assyrian, Babylonian, and potentially Greek subjugation, YHWH promises an end to foreign military transit through the land. 'For now I see with my own eyes' (<em>ki attah ra'iti ve'einai</em>) — YHWH's personal oversight is the guarantee. The verse connects the geo-political survey (vv1-7) to the coming salvation (vv9-10).</p>",
        "9": "<p>'Rejoice greatly, O daughter of Zion! Shout aloud, O daughter of Jerusalem! Behold, your king is coming to you; righteous and having salvation is he, humble and mounted on a donkey, on a colt, the foal of a donkey.' Zechariah 9:9 is one of the most precisely fulfilled messianic prophecies in the OT: Matthew (21:5) and John (12:15) both cite it explicitly at the Triumphal Entry. The verse is the theological center of the First Burden. Key terms: (1) <em>tzaddik</em> (righteous) — the king is himself righteous, not merely a just ruler; (2) <em>nosha</em> (having salvation, H3467 — either 'victorious' or 'saved by God' — the passive form means 'one who has been saved/vindicated by YHWH') — the king's victory is YHWH's work; (3) <em>ani</em> (humble, H6035 — poor, meek, afflicted — the same word used for the aniyim remnant of Zeph 3:12); (4) <em>rochev al chamor</em> (riding on a donkey) — a king on a donkey signals peace, not war (contrast a war-horse, v10 = the war-horse cut off).</p>",
        "10": "<p>'I will cut off the chariot from Ephraim and the war horse from Jerusalem; and the battle bow shall be cut off, and he shall speak peace to the nations; his dominion shall be from sea to sea, and from the River to the ends of the earth.' The messianic king brings universal peace: military instruments removed (chariot, horse, bow), peace proclaimed to the nations, dominion extending to the whole earth. The 'from sea to sea and from the River to the ends of the earth' is the covenant land promise (Gen 15:18; Ps 72:8) expanded to its maximum eschatological extent. The NT: Christ's command to lay down the sword (Matt 26:52), his proclamation of peace (John 14:27; Eph 2:14-17), and his coming universal rule (Rev 11:15).</p>",
        "11": "<p>'As for you also, because of the blood of my covenant with you, I will set your prisoners free from the waterless pit.' The 'blood of your covenant' (<em>bedam beritekh</em>) — the Sinaitic covenant ratified by blood (Exod 24:8: behold the blood of the covenant). Because of the covenant's blood-bond, YHWH commits to liberating the prisoners. 'The waterless pit' (<em>bor ein mavim</em>) echoes Joseph's pit (Gen 37:24: the pit was empty, there was no water in it) and Jeremiah's pit-prison (Jer 38:6). The liberation from the pit is both the historical return from exile and the eschatological liberation that the NT applies to Christ's descent and resurrection (cf. 1 Pet 3:19).</p>",
        "12": "<p>'Return to your stronghold, O prisoners of hope; today I declare that I will restore to you double.' The call to 'prisoners of hope' (<em>asirei hatiqvah</em>) — those who are imprisoned but hope for release — to return to the <em>betzaron</em> (stronghold, fortified place). The promise of double (<em>mishneh</em>) restoration echoes Job 42:10 (YHWH gave Job twice as much) and Isa 61:7 (instead of your shame you shall have a double portion). The double-restoration formula is the OT's overcorrection pattern: YHWH gives back more than was taken.</p>",
        "13": "<p>'For I have bent Judah as my bow; I have made Ephraim its arrow. I will stir up your sons, O Zion, against your sons, O Greece, and wield you like a warrior's sword.' YHWH as the divine archer bending Judah as his bow and Ephraim as his arrow — the reunited nation (both Judah and Ephraim/northern Israel) is YHWH's weapon. The specific mention of <em>Yavan</em> (H3120, Greece/Javan) is remarkable: the sons of Zion versus the sons of Greece anticipates the Maccabean conflict (167-164 BCE), when Jewish resistance to Hellenization under Antiochus IV (the Maccabean revolt) appeared to be YHWH's people fighting YHWH's battle against Greek cultural imperialism.</p>",
        "14": "<p>'Then the LORD will appear over them, and his arrow will go out like lightning; the Lord GOD will sound the trumpet and will march forth in the whirlwinds of the south.' YHWH as the Divine Warrior leading the battle: his arrow like lightning (<em>chetz kevaraz yetze</em>), the divine trumpet sounding (<em>yitqah beshofar</em>), the march through the storm-wind. The divine warrior theophany vocabulary (lightning, thunder, whirlwind, trumpet) echoes the Sinai theophany (Exod 19:16; 20:18) and the Hab 3 theophanic psalm. YHWH fights for his people.</p>",
        "15": "<p>'The LORD of hosts will protect them, and they shall devour, and tread down the sling stones, and they shall drink and roar as if drunk with wine, and be full like a bowl, drenched like the corners of the altar.' The victory is YHWH's protection and the people's empowered action together. The devouring and treading down the sling stones suggests the vulnerability of the enemy's weapons; the drinking-and-roaring image is the intoxication of victory. The altar-corners analogy (<em>kezaviyot hamizbeach</em>) refers to the blood of sacrifices thrown against the altar corners — the people, through battle, become a kind of living sacrifice to YHWH's purposes.</p>",
        "16": "<p>'On that day the LORD their God will save them, as the flock of his people; for like the jewels of a crown they shall shine on his land.' The reversal from battle-imagery to pastoral-imagery: those who just devoured enemies are now 'the flock of his people' (<em>tzon ammo</em>) saved by the Good Shepherd. 'Jewels of a crown' (<em>avnei nezer</em>) — precious stones of a diadem, sparkling over the land. The people who were scattered (1:19, 2:6) and imprisoned (9:11) are now jewels adorning YHWH's land.</p>",
        "17": "<p>'For how great is his goodness, and how great his beauty! Grain shall make the young men flourish, and new wine the young women.' The closing doxology: YHWH's goodness (<em>tuvo</em>) and beauty (<em>yafyo</em>) — covenant blessing expressed aesthetically. The covenant prosperity (grain and new wine) specifically blessing the young (young men and young women) is the reversal of Joel 1:10-12 where grain and new wine were destroyed and the young mourned. The restoration of the young generation's blessing is the restoration of future hope.</p>"
    },
    "10": {
        "1": "<p>'Ask rain from the LORD in the season of the spring rain, from the LORD who makes the storm clouds, and he will give them showers of rain, to everyone the vegetation in the field.' The call to seek YHWH for rain continues the theme of seeking him for all provision (ch7-8). In the agricultural context of ancient Israel, rain — especially the latter rain (<em>geshem malkosh</em>, spring rain in March-April, crucial for ripening grain) — was the most immediate test of divine blessing and the most natural arena for prayer. YHWH is the cloud-maker (<em>oseh chazizim</em>), not the Baal religion's gods of storm (Ps 29: YHWH controls the storm).</p>",
        "2": "<p>'For the household gods utter nonsense, and the diviners see lies; they tell false dreams and give empty consolation. Therefore the people wander like sheep; they are afflicted for lack of a shepherd.' The contrast with pagan divination: the <em>terafim</em> (household idols/gods, H8655) speak nonsense (<em>dibru aven</em>), the diviners see lies (<em>chazah sheker</em>), the dreamers speak vain comfort. Without true prophetic guidance, the people wander like sheep without a shepherd — a profound image of spiritual and social disorientation. The shepherd theme (central in chs 10-11) is introduced: the people need a true shepherd because the false ones have failed.</p>",
        "3": "<p>'My anger is hot against the shepherds, and I will punish the leaders; for the LORD of hosts cares for his flock, the house of Judah, and will make them like his majestic steed in battle.' YHWH's anger targets the shepherds (<em>ro'im</em>) — the political and religious leaders who have failed to shepherd the people. The punishment of the leaders (<em>atudim</em>, he-goats = strong leaders) who failed their flock is followed by YHWH's direct care for the flock. The transformation of the flock: from sheep wandering without a shepherd (v2) to 'his majestic steed in battle' (<em>sus hoddo bemilchamah</em>) — YHWH transforms the weak into the powerful.</p>",
        "4": "<p>'From him shall come the cornerstone, from him the tent peg, from him the battle bow, from him every ruler — all of them together.' The 'him' is Judah (v3 ends with 'house of Judah'): from Judah shall come the four titles of leadership: (1) <em>pinna</em> (cornerstone) — the key architectural element (cf. Isa 28:16; Ps 118:22; Matt 21:42); (2) <em>yated</em> (tent peg) — the fixed point of stability (Isa 22:23); (3) <em>qeshet milchamah</em> (battle bow) — military strength; (4) <em>yotze kol nogesh yachdav</em> (every ruler together) — comprehensive leadership. The NT applies the cornerstone (<em>pinna</em>) to Christ (Eph 2:20; 1 Pet 2:6).</p>",
        "5": "<p>'Together they shall be like mighty men in battle, trampling the foe in the mud of the streets; they shall fight because the LORD is with them, and they shall put to shame the riders on horses.' The empowered Judah/Israel: fighting like mighty men because YHWH is with them. 'Trampling the foe in the mud of the streets' — the humiliation of once-proud enemies. 'Put to shame the riders on horses' — cavalry defeated by infantry, the natural order of military strength inverted by YHWH's presence. The war-horse is cut off (9:10) but the horsemen are defeated by YHWH's empowered people.</p>",
        "6": "<p>'I will strengthen the house of Judah, and I will save the house of Joseph. I will bring them back because I have compassion on them, and they shall be as though I had not rejected them, for I am the LORD their God and I will answer them.' The reunification oracle: both Judah (southern kingdom) and Joseph/Ephraim (northern kingdom) will be restored. 'As though I had not rejected them' (<em>ki hayiti lo zenavitim</em>) — the profound statement of complete forgiveness: not just restoration but a return to the status ante of full covenant relationship, as if the rejection never happened. This is the OT anticipation of Paul's 'no condemnation' (Rom 8:1) — the slate wiped clean.</p>",
        "7": "<p>'Then Ephraim shall become like a mighty warrior, and their hearts shall be glad as with wine. Their children shall see it and be glad; their hearts shall rejoice in the LORD.' The northern tribes (Ephraim = northern Israel) restored: fighting as a mighty warrior (<em>gibbor Ephraim</em>), hearts glad as with wine (<em>yismach libbam kayayin</em>), children seeing and rejoicing. The intergenerational joy — both the current generation and their children seeing YHWH's restoration — is the completeness of the restoration promise.</p>",
        "8": "<p>'I will whistle for them and gather them in, for I have redeemed them, and they shall be as many as they were before.' YHWH whistling/signaling (<em>ashreqah lahem</em>, H8319 — to hiss/signal, the way a shepherd calls his flock) to gather the scattered. The redemption vocabulary: <em>ki feditim</em> (for I have redeemed them, from <em>fadah</em> = to ransom, H6299) — the Exodus-redemption language applied to the gathering of the exiles. 'As many as they were before' (<em>verabu kaasher rabu</em>) — the demographic restoration, population returning to the pre-exile levels.</p>",
        "9": "<p>'Though I scattered them among the nations, yet in far countries they shall remember me, and with their children they shall live and return.' YHWH scattered Israel (<em>azra'em bagoyim</em>) — the exile was YHWH's act. But the scattering was not the last word: from the far countries (<em>bammerchaqqim</em>) they shall remember (<em>yizkeruni</em>) YHWH. Memory of YHWH in the diaspora is the first movement of return — the mind turning back before the body returns (cf. Luke 15:17: he came to himself, remembering the father's house). Children born in diaspora will live and return.</p>",
        "10": "<p>'I will bring them home from the land of Egypt, and gather them from Assyria, and I will bring them to the land of Gilead and to Lebanon, till there is no room for them.' The ingathering from Egypt (south) and Assyria (north) — the two poles of ancient Near Eastern power that had dominated Israel. Gilead (Transjordan) and Lebanon (north) represent the full territorial expansion of the restored kingdom. 'Till there is no room for them' (<em>velo yimmatze lahem</em>) — the land will be too full, an overcrowding of blessing. The contrast with the current desolation (7:14: no one went to and fro).</p>",
        "11": "<p>'He shall pass through the sea of troubles and strike down the waves of the sea, and all the depths of the Nile shall be dried up. The pride of Assyria shall be laid low, and the scepter of Egypt shall depart.' The new Exodus imagery: YHWH striking the sea (Exod 14:21-22), drying up the Nile (Isa 11:15 — the tongue of the Egyptian sea), overthrowing the two great empires (Assyria and Egypt) that embody all world-power. The pattern of the Exodus (sea-crossing, Egyptian defeat) is the template for the eschatological ingathering.</p>",
        "12": "<p>'I will make them strong in the LORD, and they shall walk in his name, declares the LORD.' The ultimate goal of the ingathering: not merely physical restoration but spiritual strengthening — <em>vegibartem baADONAI</em> (I will make them strong/mighty in the LORD). Walking in YHWH's name (<em>yithaleku bishmo</em>) is the NT's walking 'in Christ' (Col 2:6), walking 'in the Spirit' (Gal 5:16). The restored people's identity is defined by YHWH's name, not their ethnicity or geography.</p>"
    },
    "11": {
        "1": "<p>'Open your doors, O Lebanon, that the fire may devour your cedars! Wail, O cypress, for the cedar has fallen, for the glorious trees are ruined! Wail, oaks of Bashan, for the thick forest has come down!' The destruction oracle opens with a lament over the cedars of Lebanon — symbols of royal power and architectural greatness (Solomon's temple used Lebanon's cedars, 1 Kgs 5:6; 6:9-10). Lebanon and Bashan were the timber regions associated with Israelite royal building programs. The fall of the great trees = the fall of the national leadership. The wailing (<em>heilu</em>) is the cry of professional mourning.</p>",
        "2": "<p>'Wail, O cypress, for the cedar has fallen, for the glorious trees are ruined! Wail, oaks of Bashan, for the thick forest has come down! The sound of the wail of the shepherds, for their glory is ruined! The sound of the roar of the lions, for the thicket of the Jordan is ruined!' The descending sequence (Lebanon → Bashan → Jordan thicket) traces the destruction from north to south through the territory of Israel. The shepherds (<em>ro'im</em>) lamenting the loss of their glory and the lions their habitat are the social and ecological consequences of the destruction. The thicket of the Jordan (<em>ge'on hayarden</em>) was the lion habitat (Jer 49:19; 50:44) — the destruction of the habitat destroys the apex predator.</p>",
        "3": "<p>See v2 for context on the descending destruction. The thicket of the Jordan represents the last stronghold of the wild — its destruction signals total ecological and social collapse. This prelude (vv1-3) sets the stage for the shepherd allegory (vv4-17) by establishing the desolation that results from failed leadership.</p>",
        "4": "<p>'Thus said the LORD my God: Become shepherd of the flock doomed to slaughter.' The command to the prophet to enact the role of shepherd of the doomed flock (<em>tzon hahareg</em>) is an enacted prophetic sign. The prophet represents YHWH's faithful shepherd sent to Israel; the flock represents Israel under the oppressive shepherds (the corrupt leaders of vv5-6). The enacted parable is similar to Ezekiel 4-5 (enacted siege signs) and Hosea 1-3 (marriage as enacted parable). The prophet embodies the rejected divine shepherd.</p>",
        "5": "<p>'Their buyers slaughter them and go unpunished, and those who sell them say, Blessed be the LORD, I have become rich, and their own shepherds have no pity on them.' The merchants who buy and slaughter the flock (= political leaders who exploit the people) are unpunished. The sellers who say 'Blessed be the LORD' while profiting from the exploitation use religious language to sanctify greed — the exact pattern of the religious leaders Jesus condemns (Mark 7:10-13; Matt 23:14). 'Their own shepherds have no pity' (<em>lo yachemlu aleikhem ro'eikhem</em>) — the leaders appointed to protect them are the source of their destruction.</p>",
        "6": "<p>'For I will no longer have pity on the inhabitants of this land, declares the LORD. Behold, I will cause each of them to fall into the hand of his neighbor, and each into the hand of his king, and they shall crush the land, and I will deliver none from their hand.' The prophetic pastoral allegory gives way to divine declaration: YHWH will not spare the corrupt covenant community. The social disintegration — every man against his neighbor — is the covenant curse of Deut 28:25, 53-57 (social cannibalism under siege). YHWH hands them over to their corrupt leaders rather than rescuing them.</p>",
        "7": "<p>'So I became the shepherd of the flock doomed to be slaughtered by the sheep traders. And I took two staffs, one I named Favor, the other I named Union. And I tended the sheep.' The prophet-shepherd takes two staffs (<em>maqlot</em>): <em>No'am</em> (Favor/Pleasantness, H5278 — the goodness and beauty of YHWH's covenant grace) and <em>Chovelim</em> (Union/Binders, H2256 — the binding together of Israel and Judah). The two staffs represent the two aspects of YHWH's covenant care: the pleasantness of his grace toward his people and the unity he maintains between the divided kingdoms.</p>",
        "8": "<p>'In one month I destroyed the three shepherds. But I became impatient with them, and they also detested me.' The 'three shepherds' (<em>shlosha haro'im</em>) destroyed in one month is one of the most debated references in Zechariah — candidates include three leadership offices (prophet, priest, king), specific historical figures (Onias III, Jason, Menelaus in the Maccabean period), or the Hellenistic kings. The point is the speed of the judgment (one month = rapidly) and the mutual revulsion: the prophet-shepherd detests the corrupt leaders; they detest him. The faithful shepherd and the corrupt shepherds cannot coexist.</p>",
        "9": "<p>'So I said, I will not be your shepherd. What is to die, let it die. What is to be destroyed, let it be destroyed. And let those who are left devour the flesh of one another.' The shepherd's resignation from his office — he withdraws his protective care. The withdrawal of divine protection leads to the worst social consequence: the people devouring each other's flesh (the siege cannibalism of Deut 28:53-57; Lam 4:10; 2 Kgs 6:29). This is not divine abandonment for its own sake but the consequence of the people's rejection of the faithful shepherd.</p>",
        "10": "<p>'And I took my staff Favor, and I broke it, annulling the covenant that I had made with all the peoples.' Breaking the first staff (<em>No'am</em> = Favor) annuls the covenant with 'all the peoples' (<em>kol ha'amim</em>) — not the covenant with Israel but the covenant-like restraint YHWH maintained over the surrounding nations (a covenant of protection against enemy action). Once the Favor staff is broken, the nations are no longer restrained from attacking Israel. The breaking of the protective covenant is not a violation of YHWH's faithfulness but the withdrawal of undeserved protection from a people that has rejected their shepherd.</p>",
        "11": "<p>'So it was annulled on that day, and the sheep traders, who were watching me, knew that it was the word of the LORD.' The sheep traders (<em>kena'anim</em>, the merchants/traffickers) recognized the enacted sign as the word of YHWH. The recognition of prophetic authority by those who profit from the sheep's exploitation is ironic — they understand the prophetic sign even as they continue their exploitation.</p>",
        "12": "<p>'Then I said to them, If it seems good to you, give me my wages; but if not, keep them. And they weighed out as my wages thirty pieces of silver.' The shepherd-prophet asks for his wages. The response: <em>shloshim kesef</em> (thirty pieces of silver, H3701). In the Mosaic law, thirty pieces of silver was the compensation for a slave gored by an ox (Exod 21:32) — a slave's value, an insult as wages for a shepherd-prophet. The historical fulfillment: the chief priests paid Judas thirty pieces of silver to betray Jesus (Matt 26:15). Matthew's explicit citation (Matt 27:9-10, attributed to Jeremiah but clearly drawing on this verse) identifies the thirty pieces of silver as the price set on the true Shepherd by his people.</p>",
        "13": "<p>'Then the LORD said to me, Throw it to the potter — the lordly price at which I was priced by them. So I took the thirty pieces of silver and threw them into the house of the LORD, to the potter.' YHWH's sarcasm: <em>ha'edar hayeqar asher yakartiy me'aleihem</em> (the magnificent price at which they priced me) — the thirty pieces of silver as an insult to YHWH himself (the shepherd represents YHWH). The potter (the word may also mean 'treasury', <em>otzar</em>) in the temple: the silver is thrown into YHWH's house. Matthew 27:5-10 records the precise fulfillment: Judas threw the thirty pieces of silver into the temple; the priests used it to buy a potter's field. Matthew's citation combines Zechariah 11:12-13 with Jeremiah 19 (the potter's field).</p>",
        "14": "<p>'Then I broke my second staff Union, annulling the brotherhood between Judah and Israel.' Breaking the second staff (<em>Chovelim</em> = Union) annuls the brotherhood between Judah and Israel — the unity of the divided kingdom. The breaking of national unity is the second stage of the rejected shepherd's withdrawal of care. Without the protective covenant (first staff) and without national unity (second staff), the community is both exposed and divided — the worst possible condition.</p>",
        "15": "<p>'Then the LORD said to me, Take once more the equipment of a foolish shepherd.' The second enacted sign: the prophet now represents not the rejected good shepherd but the worthless shepherd to come — the antithesis of the faithful shepherd. The 'equipment of a foolish shepherd' (<em>kelei ro'eh evil</em>) is the gear of an incompetent, self-serving shepherd.</p>",
        "16": "<p>'For behold, I am raising up in the land a shepherd who does not care for those being destroyed, or seek the young or heal the maimed or nourish the healthy, but devours the flesh of the fat ones, tearing off even their hooves.' The worthless shepherd's character is described by six negatives: does not care for the destroyed, does not seek the young/strayed, does not heal the broken, does not sustain the healthy, but devours the fat ones and tears off their hooves. This is the exact inversion of the good shepherd's description (Ezek 34:4, 16). The NT's false shepherds (John 10:12-13: the hired hand runs from the wolf) are the development of this anti-shepherd portrait.</p>",
        "17": "<p>'Woe to my worthless shepherd, who deserts the flock! May the sword strike his arm and his right eye! Let his arm be wholly withered, his right eye utterly blinded!' The oracle against the worthless shepherd ends the chapter with a judicial curse: the sword on his arm (the instrument of his shepherd's care — he does not use it for the sheep) and blindness of the right eye (the eye of watchful oversight — he does not watch for predators). The physical punishments correspond precisely to the failures described in v16. The worthless shepherd is punished in the very faculties he failed to use.</p>"
    },
    "12": {
        "1": "<p>Chapter 12 opens the 'Second Burden' (<em>massa</em>), which spans chapters 12-14. The superscription 'the word of the LORD concerning Israel' is unusual: the preceding oracles (chs 9-11) were about the nations; this oracle specifically targets Israel/Jerusalem. The creator-credentials: 'who stretched out the heavens and founded the earth and formed the spirit of man within him' — YHWH's authority to judge and restore Jerusalem is grounded in his cosmic creatorship. The creator of heaven and earth can reshape the destiny of his city.</p>",
        "2": "<p>'Behold, I am about to make Jerusalem a cup of staggering to all the surrounding peoples. The siege of Jerusalem will also be against Judah.' The image of Jerusalem as a cup of drunkenness (<em>saf ra'al</em>, H7196 + H7478 — a cup/basin that makes the nations reel/stagger) is the reversal of Isa 51:17-23 (the cup of YHWH's wrath given to Jerusalem is taken back and given to her enemies). The nations that attack Jerusalem will drink and stagger — the city that appeared vulnerable will prove to be an intoxicating trap for her attackers.</p>",
        "3": "<p>'On that day I will make Jerusalem a heavy stone for all the peoples. All who lift it will surely hurt themselves. And all the nations of the earth will gather against it.' A heavy stone (<em>even ma'amasah</em>) that injures all who try to lift or carry it — an image of irresistible weight. This directly addresses the Zechariah-era context: the small, returning community in Jerusalem appears to be easy pickings for the surrounding nations. YHWH promises that Jerusalem will be the stone that breaks the nations who attempt to remove or conquer it. The gathering of all nations against Jerusalem is the eschatological Armageddon (Rev 16:16; 19:19).</p>",
        "4": "<p>'On that day, declares the LORD, I will strike every horse with panic, and its rider with madness. But for the sake of the house of Judah I will keep my eyes open, when I strike every horse of the peoples with blindness.' YHWH will strike the nations' cavalry with three afflictions: <em>timmahon</em> (panic, bewilderment, H8541), <em>shigga'on</em> (madness, H7697), and <em>ivvaron</em> (blindness, H5788). The contrast: while the horses and riders of the nations are struck with panic and blindness, YHWH's eyes remain open for the house of Judah. Divine attention is the protection: YHWH who neither slumbers nor sleeps (Ps 121:4) keeps watch over his people while striking their attackers with blindness.</p>",
        "5": "<p>'Then the clans of Judah shall say to themselves, The inhabitants of Jerusalem have strength through the LORD of hosts, their God.' The recognition by Judah's clans (<em>alufei Yehudah</em>, the clan leaders of Judah outside Jerusalem) that the city's survival is YHWH's doing, not human fortification. The acknowledgment that strength comes 'through YHWH of hosts, their God' (<em>bADONAI tzvaot eloheihem</em>) is the theological center of the reversal: the restoration of covenant language ('their God') accompanying the restoration of covenant protection.</p>",
        "6": "<p>'On that day I will make the clans of Judah like a blazing pot in the midst of wood, like a flaming torch among sheaves. And they shall devour to the right and to the left all the surrounding peoples, while Jerusalem shall again be inhabited in its place, in Jerusalem.' The clan leaders of Judah become like fire among kindling — an irresistible, spreading, consuming force. The metaphor of fire among dry wood is the most powerful image of devastating effectiveness. Jerusalem, paradoxically, will be inhabited in its place while Judah's clans consume the surrounding nations — the center is secure while the perimeter is aggressive.</p>",
        "7": "<p>'And the LORD will give salvation to the tents of Judah first, that the glory of the house of David and the glory of the inhabitants of Jerusalem may not surpass that of Judah.' The order of salvation: the rural clans (tents of Judah) first, then the city (Jerusalem). This prevents pride: if the city were saved first and the rural areas afterward, Jerusalem and the Davidic house might claim superiority over Judah's villages. YHWH deliberately orders salvation to prevent hierarchical pride within the covenant community.</p>",
        "8": "<p>'On that day the LORD will protect the inhabitants of Jerusalem, so that the feeblest among them on that day shall be like David, and the house of David shall be like God, like the angel of the LORD, going before them.' The escalating empowerment: the weakest person in Jerusalem becomes David-like (David = the standard of warrior courage and YHWH-dependence); the house of David becomes like God (<em>ke'Elohim</em>), like the Angel of the LORD who went before Israel (Exod 23:20-23). The Angel of the LORD who led the Exodus is the same divine figure who now, in the eschatological battle, leads the Davidic house. The equation of 'like God' and 'like the Angel of the LORD' in the same phrase is a Christological prolepsis.</p>",
        "9": "<p>'And on that day I will seek to destroy all the nations that come against Jerusalem.' The divine warrior's purpose stated directly: <em>avaqesh lehashmid</em> (I will seek to destroy) all the nations attacking Jerusalem. The nations who come against YHWH's city come against YHWH himself; their destruction is the vindication of the city and the covenant. Verses 10-14 immediately follow with the pouring out of the spirit of grace and the mourning for the pierced one — the judgment and the salvation occur simultaneously.</p>",
        "10": "<p>'And I will pour out on the house of David and the inhabitants of Jerusalem a spirit of grace and pleas for mercy, so that, when they look on me, on him whom they have pierced, they shall mourn for him, as one mourns for an only child, and weep bitterly over him, as one weeps over a firstborn.' Zechariah 12:10 is one of the most theologically rich verses in the OT. The spirit of grace and supplication (<em>ruach chen vetachanunin</em>) is poured out — a new covenant act (cf. Ezek 36:26-27; Joel 2:28-29). The grammatical anomaly: 'they shall look to me whom they have pierced' — YHWH is the one pierced, yet the text shifts from 'me' to 'him' in the same sentence. John 19:37 cites this at the crucifixion; Rev 1:7 applies it to the parousia. The mourning is as intense as mourning for an only child (<em>yachid</em>) and a firstborn (<em>bechor</em>) — the most devastating losses in the ancient world. The mourning represents both repentance (Acts 2:37) and grief over what was done to the Messiah.</p>",
        "11": "<p>'On that day the mourning in Jerusalem will be as great as the mourning for Hadad-rimmon in the plain of Megiddo.' The comparison to the mourning for Hadad-rimmon (H1910 — possibly a location in the Jezreel Valley, or a deity associated with a mourning ritual) in the plain of Megiddo links to the mourning for King Josiah, who was mortally wounded there (2 Chr 35:24-25). The national mourning for Josiah — the greatest reforming king, cut off in his prime — was the most intense collective grief in Israel's recent memory. The eschatological mourning over the pierced one will be even greater.</p>",
        "12": "<p>'The land shall mourn, each family by itself: the family of the house of David by itself, and their wives by itself; the family of the house of Nathan by itself, and their wives by itself.' The mourning is organized by households, with men and women mourning separately — the pattern of Yom Kippur worship (the most solemn day of the Jewish calendar). The four families listed (David, Nathan, Levi, Shimei) represent royal, prophetic, priestly, and Levitical lineages — the comprehensive range of Israel's covenant leadership all united in this mourning. Nathan the son of David (2 Sam 5:14) represents the non-Solomonic branch of the Davidic line, important for the NT genealogy of Jesus (Luke 3:31).</p>",
        "13": "<p>'The family of the house of Levi by itself, and their wives by itself; the family of the Shimeites by itself, and their wives by itself.' The Levitical and Shimeite (a Levitical clan descended from Shimei son of Gershon, Num 3:21) families add the priestly class to the universal mourning. The separation of husbands and wives in mourning reflects both the privacy of intense grief and perhaps the gender-separated worship practice of the temple. The comprehensive social representation — royal, prophetic, priestly, Levitical — ensures that no class escapes or stands aloof from the communal mourning.</p>",
        "14": "<p>'And all the remaining families, each by itself, and their wives by themselves.' The all-inclusive conclusion: <em>kol hamishpachot hanisharot</em> (all the remaining families) — every family in the land joins the mourning. The mourning is truly universal: no household, clan, tribe, or class is exempt. The national mourning over the pierced one represents the moment when the entire covenant community comes to recognize the identity of the one they rejected.</p>"
    },
    "13": {
        "1": "<p>'On that day there shall be a fountain opened for the house of David and the inhabitants of Jerusalem, to cleanse them from sin and uncleanness.' The fountain for sin (<em>maqor niftach</em>) flows directly from the mourning of 12:10-14. The recognition and mourning over the pierced one is immediately followed by the opening of a fountain (<em>maqor</em>, H4726 — a spring, a source) for cleansing. This is the NT's cleansing through the blood of Christ: 'the blood of Jesus his Son cleanses us from all sin' (1 John 1:7). The fountain's dual purpose: for <em>chata't</em> (sin, H2403) and for <em>niddah</em> (impurity/uncleanness, H5079 — the Levitical term for ritual uncleanness, especially menstrual impurity). The atonement covers both moral guilt and ritual uncleanness.</p>",
        "2": "<p>'And on that day, declares the LORD of hosts, I will cut off the names of the idols from the land, so that they shall be remembered no more. And also I will remove from the land the prophets and the unclean spirit.' The purification of the land follows the opening of the cleansing fountain: the idol-names (<em>shemot ha'atzabbim</em>) cut off (= no longer remembered, no longer worshiped), the false prophets removed, and the unclean spirit (<em>ruach hatumah</em>) expelled. The sequence — fountain for sin (v1), removal of idols and false prophecy (v2-6) — is the personal and social purification that accompanies the eschatological atonement.</p>",
        "3": "<p>'And if anyone again prophesies, his father and mother who bore him will say to him, You shall not live, for you speak lies in the name of the LORD. And his father and mother who bore him shall pierce him through when he prophesies.' The severity of false prophecy in the restored community: even parents will execute a false-prophet son (cf. Deut 13:6-11: even a beloved family member who leads to idolatry must be stoned). The post-restoration community has such a heightened awareness of the cost of false prophecy (the exile was partly caused by false prophets, Jer 14:13-16; Ezek 13) that the most intimate relationships cannot shield a false prophet from judgment.</p>",
        "4": "<p>'On that day every prophet will be ashamed of his vision when he prophesies. He will not put on a hairy cloak in order to deceive.' The false prophet's self-exposure: no longer wearing the prophetic uniform (<em>aderet se'ar</em>, a hairy cloak — Elijah's distinctive dress, 2 Kgs 1:8; cf. Matt 3:4, John the Baptist's camel-hair clothing as prophetic identification). The false prophet will be ashamed to claim prophetic status and will abandon the distinguishing garment of the prophetic office.</p>",
        "5": "<p>'But he will say, I am no prophet, I am a worker of the soil, for a man sold me as a slave in my youth.' The false prophet's self-denial: claiming to be a farmer (<em>oved adamah ani</em>), not a prophet. The reference to being sold as a slave in youth may reflect the practice of debt-slavery — the claim is an attempt to disavow prophetic credentials entirely. The irony: the false prophet who sold his prophetic services to the highest bidder now claims he was the one who was sold.</p>",
        "6": "<p>'And if someone asks him, What are these wounds on your back? he will say, The wounds I received in the house of my friends.' The wounds (<em>makkot</em>) on the back/hands of the false prophet may be the marks of ecstatic prophetic self-wounding (1 Kgs 18:28: the Baal prophets cut themselves) or the marks of discipline received from those who recognized his false prophecy. 'The house of my friends' (<em>beit ahavai</em>) is the false prophet's evasive answer: the wounds came from friends, not from punishment for false prophecy. The verse may also be read as a standalone Christological passage: the wounds received in the house of friends echo John 20:25 (the marks of the nails in Jesus's hands) and the betrayal context (John 13:18: even my close friend... has lifted his heel against me).</p>",
        "7": "<p>'Awake, O sword, against my shepherd, against the man who stands next to me, declares the LORD of hosts. Strike the shepherd, and the sheep will be scattered; I will turn my hand against the little ones.' The sword oracle against the shepherd is the second most-cited verse from Zechariah in the passion narratives (after 12:10). Jesus quotes it directly in Gethsemane: 'Strike the shepherd, and the sheep will be scattered' (Matt 26:31; Mark 14:27). Key terms: (1) <em>herev uri</em> (O sword, awake!) — the sword as YHWH's instrument of judgment; (2) <em>al ro'i</em> (against my shepherd) — YHWH's own shepherd is struck; (3) <em>al ha'ish amiti</em> (against the man who stands next to me/my associate) — <em>amiti</em> (H5997) = my fellow, my associate, my close companion. This is one who stands beside YHWH in intimate relationship — not a distant servant but a divine associate. The NT identification: Christ as both YHWH's shepherd and his divine associate (<em>amiti</em>), struck by the sword of YHWH's judgment as the bearer of the world's sin (Isa 53:4-6).</p>",
        "8": "<p>'In the whole land, declares the LORD, two thirds shall be cut off and perish, and one third shall be left alive.' The two-thirds/one-third division: YHWH's refining judgment reduces the population to a remnant — two-thirds cut off and dying, one-third surviving. This is more severe than Noah's flood (in which 8 survived) but produces a refined remnant, not a purged community. The one-third who survive are the remnant who go through the refining fire. The two-thirds are not the 'more wicked'; the distinction is eschatological, not strictly moral — it is the remnant theology that runs throughout the prophets (Isa 1:9; 6:13; 10:20-21; Amos 5:3).</p>",
        "9": "<p>'And I will put this third into the fire, and refine them as one refines silver, and test them as gold is tested. They will call upon my name, and I will answer them. I will say, They are my people; and they will say, The LORD is my God.' The remnant is refined in fire — not destroyed but purified. The silver-refining and gold-testing metaphors (Ps 66:10; Isa 48:10; Mal 3:2-3) describe the process of purification through suffering: impurities burned away, the precious metal revealed. The chapter climaxes with the covenant formula restored: <em>hemmah yiqre'u vishmi va'ani e'eneh otam amarti ammi hemma vehem yomru YHWH Elohai</em> (they shall call on my name and I will answer; I will say, they are my people; they will say, YHWH is my God). The broken covenant — shattered in ch7-11 — is restored in its simplest, most intimate form: the mutual declaration of belonging. This is the covenant formula of Hos 2:23 ('I will say, You are my people; and he shall say, You are my God') completed through the fire of the cross.</p>"
    }
}


def main():
    c = load_comm('mkt-context', 'zechariah')
    merge_comm(c, DATA)
    save_comm('mkt-context', 'zechariah', c)
    total = sum(len(v) for v in DATA.values())
    print(f'zechariah mkt-context: added up to {total} verses across ch8-13')


if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
